{{Orphan|date=June 2013}} {{Infobox film | name = I Love Hip Hop in Morocco | image = | alt = | caption = | film name = <!--(for non-English films: film's name in its native language)--> | director = Josh Asen | producer = <!-- or: |producers = --> | writer = <!-- or: |writers = --> | screenplay = | story = | based on = <!-- {{based on|title of the original work|writer of the original work}} --> | starring = | narrator = <!-- or: |narrators = --> | music = | cinematography = | editing = | studio = <!-- or: |production companies = --> | distributor = <!-- or: |distributors = --> | released = {{film date|2007}} | runtime = | country = United States | language = | budget = | gross = <!--(please use condensed and rounded values, e.g. "£11.6 million" not "£11,586,221")--> }} '''''I Love Hip Hop in Morocco''''' is a 2007 film by Josh Asen who decided to film hip hop in Morocco with his friend Jennifer Needle. While interviewing Moroccan hip hop artists, they told him that they needed concerts to promote their music. Asen managed to get the U.S. Embassy and Coca-Cola to sponsor a music festival.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.jewishexponent.com/article/15635/Hip_to_HipHop__in_Morocco/ |title=Hip to Hip-Hop ... in Morocco |date=March 20, 2008 |work=Jewish Exponent |accessdate=December 30, 2011}}</ref>
Groups of musicians started the country's first hip hop tour in three Moroccan cities - [[Meknes]], [[Marrakesh]], and [[Casablanca]]. The three concerts brought in thousands of audience members.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://ucriverside.academia.edu/OykuPotuogluCook/Papers/1197979/_I_Love_Hip_Hop_in_Morocco._Film_Video_._Josh_Ansen_and_Jennifer_Needleman._Anthropology_Review_Database_January_28th_2011_ |title="I Love Hip Hop in Morocco." (Film:Video). Josh Ansen and Jennifer Needleman. Anthropology Review Database (January 28th, 2011) |author=Öykü Potuoğlu-Cook |date=January 28, 2011 |work=George Mason University |accessdate=December 31, 2011}}</ref>
The film ended up as a 2007 documentary about the musicians' struggles and what it is like to rap in a Muslim country.<ref>{{cite book |title=Rock the Casbah: Rage and Rebellion Across the Islamic World |last=Wright |first=Robin |year=2011 |publisher=Simon and Schuster |isbn=978-1-4391-0316-6 |page=121 |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=numqfH3FgY8C&pg=PA121 |accessdate=December 31, 2011}}</ref> The documentary mainly focuses on DJ Key, H-Kayne, Bigg, Fati Show, and the hip hop group Fnaire.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.accessmylibrary.com/article-1G1-234308692/love-hip-hop-morocco.html |title=I Love Hip Hop in Morocco.(Masizakhe: Building Each Other)(Brief article)(Video recording review) |author=Bill Baars |date=August 1, 2010 |work=Library Journal |accessdate=December 31, 2011}}</ref>
