{{update|date=September 2018}} {{Use dmy dates|date=August 2018}} {{Infobox sports league | title = Oceanic Pro League | logo = Oceanic_Pro_League_logo.png | caption = Oceanic Pro League logo | last_season = OPL 2018 Split 1 | upcoming_season = OPL 2019 Split 1 | sport = ''[[League of Legends]]'' | Current Champions = Dire Wolves | founded = 2015 | commissioner = | motto = | owner = [[Riot Games]] | countries = | teams = | related_comps = | website = {{url|oce.lolesports.com/}} | footnotes =
}} '''Oceanic Pro League''' ('''OPL''') is a professional league for ''[[League of Legends]]'' teams from Australia and other countries in Oceania. Current Champions are the LG Dire Wolves. Oceanic Pro League has a YouTube Channel called the [https://www.youtube.com/user/RiotGamesOceania League of Legends Oceania] this is the home of the OPL and OCS.
== History == === 2015 === The league was announced in February 2015, along with two other competitions: the [[Challenger Championship]] and the [[Oceanic Open Ladder]].<ref name="announcement1">{{Cite web|url=http://oce.leagueoflegends.com/en/news/esports/esports-editorial/2015-oceanic-competitive-season|title=2015 Oceanic Competitive Season|last=Riot Benji|date=6 February 2015|publisher=oce.leagueoflegends.com|access-date=11 August 2016}}</ref><ref name="announcement2">{{Cite web|url=http://www.pcgamer.com/oceania-gets-its-first-league-of-legends-esports-league|title=Oceania gets its first League of Legends eSports League|last=Shaun Prescott|date=5 February 2015|publisher=pcgamer.com|access-date=11 August 2016}}</ref> The prize money for the first season of the OPL was $32,000, and the winners of the first split, the Chiefs, went to Istanbul for the [[International Wildcard Invitational 2015]],<ref name="announcement3">{{Cite web|url=http://www.ign.com/articles/2015/02/05/riot-launches-first-league-of-legends-oceanic-esports-league|title=Riot Launches First League of Legends Oceanic eSports League – IGN|last=Jenna Pitcher|date=4 February 2015|publisher=ign.com|access-date=11 August 2016}} </ref> the qualifying tournament for the [[2015 Mid-Season Invitational|Mid-Season Invitational 2015]], where they placed fifth, missing the chance to play in the main stage of the competition.<ref name="iwci2015">{{Cite web|url=http://www.esports-betting.pro/news/lol/iwci-istanbul-2015-recap|title=Recap IWCI Istanbul 2015 – League of Legends|date=28 April 2015|publisher=ign.com|access-date=11 August 2016}} </ref>
Before the second split, the venue for the Grand Final was announced – [[Luna Park Sydney]].<ref name="sydney1">{{Cite web|url=http://www.gameplanet.com.au/news/g5546ee4163239/Sydneys-Luna-Park-to-house-LoL-Oceanic-Pro-League-final|title=Sydney's Luna Park to house LoL Oceanic Pro League final – Gameplanet Australia|last=Matt Maguire|date=4 May 2015|publisher=gameplanet.com.au|access-date=12 August 2016}} </ref> Tickets for the event cost A$15, and the teams competed for a place in IWCT 2015.<ref name="sydney2">{{Cite web|url=http://www.nonfictiongaming.com/2015/05/league-legends-invades-luna-park-opl-grand-final|title=League of Legends Invades Luna Park for the OPL Grand Final|last=Daniel|date=5 May 2015|publisher=nonfictiongaming.com|access-date=12 August 2016}} </ref> Champions of the second split, Chiefs,<ref name="sydney3">{{Cite web|url=http://stevivor.com/2015/08/chiefs-take-down-legacy-to-secure-oceanic-pro-league-final|title=Chiefs take down Legacy to secure Oceanic Pro League Final|last=Hamish Lindsay|date=10 August 2015|publisher=stevivor.com|access-date=12 August 2016}} </ref> came second at IWCT 2015 and missed the 2015 League of Legends World Championship, losing in the final to the team Bangkok Titans from Thailand with a score of 1:3.<ref name="iwct">{{Cite web|url=http://2015.na.lolesports.com/iwc/2015/2015iwcqualifierturkey/matches/finals/chiefs-esports-club-vs-bangkok-titans|title=Chiefs eSports Club vs Bangkok Titans|publisher=lolesports|access-date=12 August 2016}}</ref> In September of the same year, Team Immunity was suspended from participating in the [[List of League of Legends leagues and tournaments|PLA]] and other OPL competitions for a period of two years due to non-payment of player salaries.<ref name="immunity">{{Cite web|url=http://www.cybersport.ru/news/team-immunity-ne-smogut-vystupat-na-ofitsialnykh-turnirakh-po-lige-legend-2-goda/|title=Immunity не смогут выступать на турнирах по Лиге Легенд 2 года|last=ShamanX|date=22 September 2015|publisher=cybersport.ru|access-date=12 August 2016}} </ref>
=== 2016 === In January 2016 it was announced that the Oceanic Challenger Series will become a league with a seven-week season and playoffs, and the [[Round-robin tournament|round-robin]] stage of will take place in a [[best of three]] format, which will stretch the game week to three days.<ref name="change2015">{{Cite web|url=http://oce.leagueoflegends.com/en/page/announcing-2016-opl-season|title=Announcing the 2016 OPL season!|date=5 January 2016|publisher=oce.leagueoflegends.com|access-date=12 August 2016}} </ref> The venue for the grand final of the second split of 2016, where the IWCQ 2016 representative from Oceania will be chosen, was announced as the [[Courier Mail Piazza]].<ref name="change2015-2">{{Cite web|url=http://www.sunshinecoastdaily.com.au/news/lol-esports-event-comes-to-brisbane/2894275/|title=Pro League of Legends event comes to Brisbane|date=11 January 2016|publisher=sunshinecoastdaily.com.au|access-date=12 August 2016}} </ref>
The winners of the first split of the second season of the Oceania league were the Chiefs, winning against Legacy in the grand final with a score of 3:2.<ref name="final">{{Cite web|url=http://www.theroar.com.au/2016/04/06/chiefs-defeat-rivals-legacy-thrilling-opl-grand-final/|title=Chiefs defeat rivals Legacy in thrilling OPL grand final|last=Russell Noble|date=6 April 2016|publisher=theroar.com.au|access-date=15 August 2016}} </ref> The Chiefs were allowed to participate in third qualifiers for the international competition,<ref name="change2015-3">{{Cite web|url=http://ru.lolesports.com/articles/246-IWCI-2016--SHefy--iz-Avstralii|title=IWCI 2016: Шефы из Австралии|last=Paseka|date=7 April 2016|publisher=ru.lolesports.com|access-date=15 August 2016}} </ref> but they failed to qualify for the main tournament, taking sixth place in the group stage with three wins and four defeats.<ref name="iwcigr">{{Cite web|url=http://ru.lolesports.com/iwci/iwci_2016_spring/standings|title=IWCI 2016|publisher=ru.lolesports.com|access-date=15 August 2016}}</ref> The Chiefs and Legacy met again in the final of the second split, where the Chiefs were victorious with a score of 3:0.<ref name="secondsplit2016-1">{{Cite web|url=http://www.gameplanet.co.nz/news/g57b102f2c0abe/Chiefs-defend-title-in-League-of-Legends-OPL-Grand-Final/|title=Chiefs defend title in League of Legends OPL Grand Final – Gameplanet New Zealand|last=Andi Garnett|date=15 August 2016|publisher=ru.lolesports.com|access-date=15 August 2016}} </ref>
